Introduction To the Project¶

In this Project, we try extract any useful information about each appointment and visualize our findings in a manner than is easy to follow in order to help us better understand the factors that affect people's show/no-show rate.

The reason for choosing this project is an interest in discovering what other factors contribute to a phenomenon like Not showing up to an appointment someone scheduled for himself.Especially, medical appointments.

Libraries used: Pandas, Numpy, Matplotlib and Seaborn.

Questions To Answer¶

1.showing visual representations of the categorical data columns

2.which property matters the most when it comes to showing/not-showing up to appoinments ?¶

(Age, Neighbourhood, Scholarship, SMS)

3.which illness matters the most when it comes to showing/non-showing up to appoinments ?¶

(Hypertension, Diabetes, Handicapped, Alcoholism)

4.does the date of 'SheduledDay' or 'AppoinmentDay' have any Effect on show-up rate?¶

5.does the difference between 'ScheduledDay' and 'AppointmentDay' Effect show-up rate ?¶

Dataset¶

we will be investigating the dataset 'noshowappointments-kagglev2-may-2016.csv' from Kaggle. - link

This dataset contains data about each appointment's date(s), and weither or not they recieved SMS.Futhermore, It contians the Patient's Gender, Age and Diagnosis.

Columns:

  • PatientId
  • AppointmentID
  • Gender
  • ScheduledDay
  • AppointmentDay
  • Age
  • Neighbourhood
  • Scholarship
  • Hipertension
  • Diabetes
  • Alcoholism
  • Handcap
  • SMS_received
  • No-show

def clean_age(age):
    """ removes any negative age values and normalize them to 0."""
    if age < 0:
        return 0
    else:
        return age

df['Age'] = df['Age'].apply(clean_age)

"""This Seciton Creates two variables that will be later used in analysis:

'top_10_Neighbourhood_labels' : contains the top 10 neighbourhoods' names with the highest count in the dataset + 'Others'
'top_10_Neighbourhood_values' : contains the top 10 neighbourhoods' values with the highest count in the dataset 
                                + sum of all the rest (others) """

top_10_Neighbourhood = df.Neighbourhood.value_counts() 
top_10_Neighbourhood_labels = list(top_10_Neighbourhood[:10].keys())
top_10_Neighbourhood_labels.append("OTHERS")

top_10_Neighbourhood_values = list(top_10_Neighbourhood[:10].values)
top_10_Neighbourhood_values.append(top_10_Neighbourhood[10:].sum())

Age¶

In [31]:
sns.kdeplot(x='Age',hue ='No_show',data=df,bw_adjust=0.25,common_norm = False);
plt.title("Age / show-up Percentage",fontsize=20);

in the upper section of the 'Age' values (5 to 30), the Patients have a higher probaility to not show up compared to patients that are older (30 to 60).

A large amount of the data has an empty age column (=0). This points that a lot of patients have undocumented ages, which will hurt the validity of any conclusions we take based on the age of the patients. Recommended that we report back to the client that there is a data gathering problem with 'age' category. However, these columns will not be dropped as the rest of the data in them seems to be of real patients...

SMS¶

In [7]:
sns.displot(x='No_show',hue ='SMS_received',data=df, kind = 'hist',
            multiple = 'dodge', shrink = 0.8,common_norm = False, stat = 'percent');
plt.title("SMS Received / show-up Percentage",fontsize=20);

More patients that show up didn't receive an SMS. And more patients that don't show up received an SMS.

The number of people that don't show up when they dont recieve an SMS is lower than the people that don't show after getting the SMS. This may suggest that there is a problem with the SMS system that might be affecting the show-up rate negatively.

Observations:

  • a lot of patients have undocumented ages (age equals zero). but, in the upper section of the 'Age' values (5 to 30), the Patients have a higher probaility to not show up compared to patients that are older (30 to 60).
  • increase in the people with scholarships that don't show up over people that don't showup without a scholarship.
  • More patients that show up didn't receive an SMS. And more patients that don't show up received an SMS.

a lot of patients have undocumented ages, which will hurt the validity of any conclusions we take based on the age of the patients. Recommended that we report back to the client that there is a data gathering problem with 'age' category. However from the data availibie, the Patients under 30 years old have a higher probaility to not show up compared to patients that are older.

In Addition, There is a slight increase in people with scholarships that don't show up. Furthermore, The number of people that don't show up when they recieve an SMS is higher than the people that don't show after getting the SMS. This may suggest that there is a problem with the SMS system as it has the reverse effect than intended.

hand = df #copy dataframe 


def handicap_bool(row):
    """identifies if a Patient is Handicapped or not

    Arguments: row ==> a row in the dataset 

    Returns: 'Yes' or 'No'.
    """
    if row['Handicapped'] == 0:
        return 'No'
    else:
        return 'Yes'
hand['Handicapped2'] = hand.apply(handicap_bool,axis = 1)
hand.head()

Q5: does the difference between 'ScheduledDay' and 'AppointmentDay' Effect show-up rate ?¶

In [21]:
def difference_in_days(row):
    """Calculates the difference in days between 'AppointmentDay' and 'ScheduledDay'

    Arguments: row ==> a row/tuple in the dataset

    Returns: difference in days (int) ==> number of days between both dates.
    """

    difference_in_days = row['AppointmentDay'] - row['ScheduledDay']
    difference_in_days = difference_in_days.days
    
    if difference_in_days <= 0:
        return np.nan
    else:
        return difference_in_days
    
df['difference_in_days'] = df.apply(difference_in_days, axis = 1)

Observations:

The shorter the difference in days, the less likely the patients are to not show up. However, the further you go, the more the effect is weaker, to the point it becomes negligable.

Example, Someone who has the difference between the 'Appointment Day' and the 'Scheduled Day' less than 10 days. has a higher chance to show up. but, someone who has the difference more than 50+ days has an equal chance to show/not-show.

Final Conclusions:¶

showing visual representations of the categorical data columns :

  • Showing up: 79% Show, 21% No Show
  • Gender: 65% Female, 35% Male
  • Neighbourhood: 81 different Neighbourhoods, Data almost evenly distributed. Hinting that this Data might be from a large clinc where people come from different Neighbourhoods instead of a local clinic that only has patients from nearby areas
  • Scholarships: around 10% have Scholarships
  • Hypertension: around 20% have Hypertension
  • Diabetesaround 7% are diabetic
  • Alcoholism: 3% of the data
  • Handicapped: only 2% of data is handicapped, and they're split up into 4 different levels and the majority of handicapped patients are of type 'level 1'
  • SMS: around 32% recieved SMS

which property matters the most when it comes to showing/not-showing up to appoinments ?

  • a lot of patients have undocumented ages (age equals zero). but, in the upper section of the 'Age' values (5 to 30), the Patients have a higher probaility to not show up compared to patients that are older (30 to 60).
  • increase in the people with scholarships that don't show up over people that don't showup without a scholarship.
  • More patients that show up didn't receive an SMS. And more patients that don't show up received an SMS.

a lot of patients have undocumented ages, which will hurt the validity of any conclusions we take based on the age of the patients. Recommended that we report back to the client that there is a data gathering problem with 'age' category. However from the data availibie, the Patients under 30 years old have a higher probaility to not show up compared to patients that are older.

In Addition, There is a slight increase in people with scholarships that don't show up. Furthermore, The number of people that don't show up when they recieve an SMS is higher than the people that don't show after getting the SMS. This may suggest that there is a problem with the SMS system as it has the reverse effect than intended.

which illness matters the most when it comes to showing/non-showing up to appoinments ?

  • higher chance to show-up for Patients that have Hypertension, Diabetes or are Handicapped over all other cateogires.

Almost all the graphs showed that Patients with underlying medical conditions have a higher chance of showing up. except Alcoholism, which doesn't have an affect.Furthermore, Handicapped people have a higher chance to show-up except level 4 Handicaps, which have a lower chance to show up.
